    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-4724964">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-4724964">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4724964)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4724964">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3938622); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3938622&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227328" alt="The Great Hippo" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3938622)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/the-great-hippo" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3938622); return false;" >The Great Hippo</a></span> <span class="odate time_1595284477 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">20 Jul 2020 22:34</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4724964">
									

<p>So&#8230;</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">FEEDBACK!</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>The prose here feels a little stilted in a lot of places. That might seem like a weird complaint, given that this is supposed to be an amateur wiki, but&#8230; sentences like this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>By the time it was fully operational in 1872, approximately 50% of Saltville's population—men, women, and children—held a job in the factory, even after the federal abolition of child labor in 1881[5], behavior which was allowed due to the fact that the government of New York State never sent regulators to the King Textiles plant.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&#8212; are a mouthful to read. A lot of this stuff could be broken up to make it feel less of a slog. I'm also confused by this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>On October 15th, 1895—the birthday of Malcolm King, Founder and President of King Textiles—the factory burned to the ground in an act of arson. Originally attributed to a communist element[4], the culprit in the arson case was found to have been Jakob Shriner, a German immigrant who was illiterate in English and had no familiarity with either the name or the works of Karl Marx. Shriner's statement was used to send him to an asylum on Wards Island, New York City, where he died of smallpox in 1899. Until his death, he claimed that his statement was entirely true.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>&#8212; because we get no reference to what this statement is, what it referred to, or what it's about &#8212; but the framing implies it had something to do with a 'communist element' and 'Karl Marx'. I'd actually just cut the statement out here and leave his motivations unidentified (until we get to the statement).</p>
<p>I want to take a moment and show you what I mean about breaking some of these sentences up. Here's what you've got in the statement:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Have you ever slept in a room with a ticking clock? The noise it makes, it can be sickening. If the gears stop, your heart can skip beats. It is how my grandfather died, so we never, ever keep clocks in the house.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Now, reread this, but with <em>one</em> minor change:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Have you ever slept in a room with a ticking clock? The noise it makes, it can be sickening. If the gears stop, your heart can skip beats. <span style="color: blue">It is how my grandfather died. We never keep clocks in the house.</span></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The change is subtle &#8212; but by breaking the last sentence into two sentences, those last two statements gain significantly more impact: &quot;It is how my grandfather died. We never keep clocks in the house.&quot;</p>
<p>There's a lot of this going on throughout the article &#8212; points where you could break sentences up to create better emphasis, better impact, so on. As it is, a lot of the prose ends up feeling like it rambles &#8212; you've got sentence after sentence with two, three, and even four clauses in them.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>When the clock was first put in at the factory, we were told that we did not have to use it, not at first. I avoided it as much as I could, but was told I would be given a three-cent raise if I started using it, and times were, ah, not so good, so I started using it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Have you read many letters from this period and time? I would recommend doing so &#8212; this doesn't &quot;feel&quot; like it comes from the period to me (admittedly this is an <em>extremely</em> subjective thing to say, but&#8230;). If you're interested getting a stronger sense of the 'style' of that time, I'd recommend looking around for some first-hand documents re: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle_Shirtwaist_Factory_fire">the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire</a> (plenty of newspapers, letters, etc!). It's not 1895, but 1911 is close enough to get you there.</p>
<p>There's a lot of things here and there that I feel like could be improved on to give this a lot more oomph. Here's another example:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Shriner died of smallpox in an asylum in Ward's Island, New York City four years later. While given a chance of freedom (or at least better living conditions) if he recanted, he refused to do so, saying that what he said was true until he died.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Would consider:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>When given a chance for freedom in exchange for recanting his statement, Shriner refused. He died of smallpox four years later.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That's all you need &#8212; it's much stronger (also, with something like this, you don't need to bring up him standing by his statement earlier &#8212; *this* is the point when we learn he insisted it was true up until he died).</p>
<p>So&#8230; in summary!</p>
<p><strong>What I like:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The imagery of children being woven into shirts.</li>
<li>The references to Moloch.</li>
<li>The whole setpiece of a factory like this; exploring its history, etc. I like the whole idea of &quot;oh hey Parawatch is a wiki, isn't it? So let's have wiki entries!&quot;.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>What I dislike:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The pacing and narrative feel disjointed. Shriner's statement was too grandiose; the lead-up to it didn't feel like it sufficiently built up to it. I never got a sense of atmosphere. I never felt like this place was actually <em>real</em>.</li>
<li>The prose felt pretty clunky in a lot of places.</li>
<li>I'm not entirely sure that this article shouldn't just be&#8230; an SCP? A tale? On one hand, I'm down for more Parawatch stuff; on the other hand, this kind of feels like it's <em>too</em> anomalous.</li>
<li>I'm torn on the footnotes. On one hand, it's a cool idea; on the other hand, it feels a bit distracting (especially since they don't actually lead or refer to anything).</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>What I think could work better:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>I think Shriner shouldn't even come up until much later. Start with the factory; build its atmosphere. Let us know it burned down because of arson, but don't let us know by who or why. Introduce Shriner close to the statement.</li>
<li>The point here is to get us thinking about this factory as a creepy place that <em>actually</em> existed. I like the bit about the population of the town versus the size of the factory &#8212; more stuff like that (though maybe a little more subtle).</li>
<li>I mentioned it above, but&#8230; seriously, if you haven't already &#8212; read up on the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangle_Shirtwaist_Factory_fire">Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire</a>. Use that as your template. I mention in my advice for Parawatch articles that a strong approach is to start with the real and creep your way into the unreal &#8212; and the Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire is a great way to do that.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Hopefully, none of the above comes off as pushy. I should emphasize that I think this is a cool idea, and I <em>like</em> what you're going for &#8212; I just don't think the execution really worked for me. Also, obviously &#8212; take my opinion here with prescription grade salt!</p>
<p>Good luck with the article!</p>
<p><strong>ETA:</strong> Reglancing through this post, it feels a smidge harsh and/or arrogant of me? If that's how it's coming off, I apologize &#8212; typed all this out in a hurry inbetween tasks (life's been pretty busy, recently!). Just wanted to emphasize that all of the above is my opinion &#8212; nothing more.</p>

							</div>

								
